  "prompt": "Which enzyme uses both NAD+ and NADP+ as a coenzyme?",
  "response": "The enzyme that can use both NAD+ and NADP+ as coenzymes is **malate dehydrogenase**. This enzyme catalyzes the reversible reaction of malate to oxaloacetate, and it can utilize either NAD+ or NADP+ depending on the specific isoform and the context within the metabolic pathways in which it is involved. Different tissues may express different isoforms of malate dehydrogenase that preferentially use one coenzyme over the other, but the capability to use both is a characteristic of some forms of the enzyme.",
